49:58.200 --> 50:01.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In tonight's In My Humble
Opinion, she offers some advice
that counters what she and her

50:01.700 --> 50:03.700 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
peers were raised to believe.

50:03.700 --> 50:05.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAROLINE KITCHENER, Author,
"Post Grad: Five Women and Their
First Year Out of College":

50:05.700 --> 50:10.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When I was a kid, Dr. Barbie was
the only Barbie in my closet,
and Disney princess movies

50:10.000 --> 50:15.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
always prompted the same
conversation with my mother:
Happy endings absolutely do not

50:17.400 --> 50:19.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
require a Prince Charming.

50:19.466 --> 50:24.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
All the adult women in my life
had to fight against the same
expectations: Get married,

50:25.400 --> 50:27.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
have kids, let someone
else make money.

50:27.700 --> 50:32.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And so they were intent
on creating a new set
of expectations for me.

50:34.700 --> 50:38.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Over the years, I became more
and more convinced: Marriage,
even a serious relationship, was

50:41.633 --> 50:43.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a kind of weakness.

50:43.700 --> 50:45.833 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Strong women didn't need anyone.

50:45.833 --> 50:50.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
While I was in college, my
female friends and I were
pressured to lean in and strive

50:52.833 --> 50:57.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for one particular kind
of success: the best, most
fulfilling career possible.

50:59.400 --> 51:03.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For high-achieving women my
age, romantic relationships
were supposed to be far less

51:03.633 --> 51:08.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
important, put on the back
burner until we were well on
our way to a corner office.

51:08.633 --> 51:13.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This was where my values
started to clash with real life.

51:15.666 --> 51:19.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
After graduation, I was going
to write a book, and all of my
writing contacts were in New

51:19.266 --> 51:21.833 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
York.

51:21.833 --> 51:25.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There, I would have a
much stronger professional
network than I would
living in any other city.

51:25.233 --> 51:27.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But my boyfriend
got a job in D.C.

51:27.800 --> 51:32.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When I started telling people
that I was moving to D.C. to be
with Robert, they all gave me

51:34.000 --> 51:36.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
this sort of sad, pitying look.

51:36.233 --> 51:38.933 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They said things like: "Really?

51:38.933 --> 51:42.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But you're so young."

51:42.566 --> 51:47.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I spent my first year after
graduation shadowing four
of my female classmates
and writing about

51:47.066 --> 51:50.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
their transition from
college to real life.

51:50.166 --> 51:52.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It was a rough year.

51:52.700 --> 51:57.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our entire lives, we'd
been surrounded by this
big, supportive community,
parents, teachers,

51:58.800 --> 52:01.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a group of friends our own age.

52:01.733 --> 52:06.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
When all that went away,
we felt more alone than
we ever had before.

52:07.600 --> 52:09.400 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We wanted to lean on a partner.

52:09.400 --> 52:13.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And that made us feel
intensely guilty.

52:13.000 --> 52:18.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Sometimes, though, relationships
can help us find our footing
in an entirely new world.

52:20.533 --> 52:25.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My point isn't that all women
should prioritize relationships
after graduation, just that

52:25.533 --> 52:29.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
those of us who do shouldn't
be demonized for it.

52:29.400 --> 52:33.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Guys who follow their
girlfriends don't get
the same judgment.

52:33.700 --> 52:38.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Instead, they're often
celebrated for being
progressive or modern.

52:40.133 --> 52:43.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
People say, that's so sweet,
or, wow, he really loves her.

52:45.933 --> 52:50.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we should ask ourselves why
those different reactions exist,
and why young women continue

52:52.500 --> 52:56.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to be judged for making
the same decisions as men.

